  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>featured snippet</strong> is a boxed answer that Google displays above the regular organic results — often called <strong>position zero</strong>. Google automatically extracts these answers from web pages that already rank on the first page and displays them to answer the query directly. Featured snippets appear in roughly 12% of queries and capture <strong>approximately 8% of the total clicks</strong> for those queries.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Queries with snippets</div>
            <div class="tms-value">~12%</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">On-Page SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">CTR captured</div>
            <div class="tms-value">~8% average</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Winning a featured snippet is one of the highest-leverage moves in SEO. You skip the #1 organic result and appear above everything else — often with your brand voice reading the answer aloud on voice assistants and feeding AI Overviews.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a featured snippet?</h2>
        <p>A featured snippet is a specialized SERP feature that appears above the standard blue links. Google introduced them in 2014 to answer questions faster, and they've since become the primary source for voice-search answers and a major source for AI Overview citations.</p>
        <p>The key mechanics:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Extracted, not authored.</strong> You don't submit a featured snippet — Google picks the text from an existing page.</li>
          <li><strong>First-page requirement.</strong> You must already rank in the top 10 for the query to be eligible.</li>
          <li><strong>Format-matched.</strong> Google picks the format (paragraph, list, table) based on the query type.</li>
          <li><strong>Position zero.</strong> The snippet appears above organic result #1, but the source URL is also removed from the traditional #1 position.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Featured snippets vs AI Overviews (2026 update)</div>
          <p>Google confirmed in 2024 that featured snippets continue to appear even on queries that trigger AI Overviews. In fact, featured snippets are one of the primary citation sources AI Overviews pull from — meaning ranking the snippet earns your brand a citation in the AI answer as well.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why featured snippets matter</h2>
        <p>Getting a featured snippet is the closest thing to jumping ranks without ranking better. Four reasons every SEO chases them:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Position above #1.</strong> You outrank the top organic result even if your traditional ranking is #4 or #7.</li>
          <li><strong>Voice search.</strong> Google Assistant reads the featured snippet answer aloud. If your brand owns the snippet, you own the voice answer.</li>
          <li><strong>AI Overview citations.</strong> Google's AI Overview pulls answers from featured snippets. Winning the snippet gets your URL cited in the AI answer box too.</li>
          <li><strong>Brand authority signal.</strong> Being the extracted answer is a soft authority signal — visitors treat you as the expert source.</li>
          <li><strong>Long-tail domination.</strong> Sites with lower domain authority can win snippets on well-structured content even against bigger competitors.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Google picks a featured snippet</h2>
        <p>Google's ranking algorithms select the snippet candidate that best answers the query in a compact, extractable format.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># The snippet-selection pipeline</span><br>
          Query enters <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Google identifies question intent<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Ranks first-page candidates by relevance<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Scans candidates for extractable structured answer<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Picks format: paragraph / list / table<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Extracts 40-60 word answer OR list items OR table rows<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Displays as featured snippet above organic
        </div>

        <h3>What makes a page snippet-friendly</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>A question-matching H2 or H3 heading</li>
          <li>A concise 40-60 word answer immediately after the heading</li>
          <li>Clean HTML structure (proper <code>&lt;h2&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;ol&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;ul&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;table&gt;</code>)</li>
          <li>Direct subject-verb-object writing without hedging</li>
          <li>Format matching what Google currently shows for the query</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">The 4 types of featured snippets</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Share of snippets</th><th>Best HTML</th><th>Best query type</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Paragraph</strong></td>
                <td>~70%</td>
                <td>H2 question + 40-60 word paragraph</td>
                <td>"What is" / "Why does"</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Ordered list</strong></td><td>~15%</td><td>H2 + <code>&lt;ol&gt;</code> with 4-8 steps</td><td>"How to" / step-by-step</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Unordered list</strong></td><td>~12%</td><td>H2 + <code>&lt;ul&gt;</code> with parallel items</td><td>"Types of" / "Best" lists</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Table</strong></td><td>~3%</td><td>H2 + <code>&lt;table&gt;</code> with clean rows</td><td>Comparisons, specs, pricing</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Video</strong></td><td>Growing</td><td>YouTube with chapters + transcript</td><td>"How to" (visual)</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real featured snippet examples</h2>
        <p>Four real featured snippets and what makes them work.</p>

        <h3>1. Paragraph snippet for "what is content marketing"</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># HubSpot's page structure that wins the snippet</span><br>
          &lt;h2&gt;What is content marketing?&lt;/h2&gt;<br>
          &lt;p&gt;Content marketing is a strategic marketing approach focused on<br>
          creating and distributing valuable, relevant content to attract and<br>
          retain an audience — and drive profitable customer action.&lt;/p&gt;<br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># 42 words. Direct. First paragraph after H2.</span>
        </div>

        <h3>2. Numbered list snippet for "how to tie a tie"</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Real Men Real Style wins with structured HTML</span><br>
          &lt;h2&gt;How to tie a tie&lt;/h2&gt;<br>
          &lt;ol&gt;<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;li&gt;Start with wide end on the right...&lt;/li&gt;<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;li&gt;Cross wide end over narrow end...&lt;/li&gt;<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;li&gt;Pass wide end up through loop...&lt;/li&gt;<br>
          &lt;/ol&gt;
        </div>

        <h3>3. Bullet list snippet for "types of coffee"</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          &lt;h2&gt;Types of coffee drinks&lt;/h2&gt;<br>
          &lt;ul&gt;<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;li&gt;Espresso&lt;/li&gt;<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;li&gt;Cappuccino&lt;/li&gt;<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;li&gt;Latte&lt;/li&gt;<br>
          &lt;/ul&gt;
        </div>

        <h3>4. Table snippet for "iPhone 15 specs"</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          &lt;h2&gt;iPhone 15 specifications&lt;/h2&gt;<br>
          &lt;table&gt;<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;th&gt;Feature&lt;/th&gt;&lt;th&gt;Spec&lt;/th&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Display&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;6.1"&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;<br>
          &lt;/table&gt;
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Featured snippet vs knowledge panel — which is which</h2>
        <p>Both appear above traditional results. Different mechanics.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Featured snippet</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Text extracted from a ranking web page</li>
              <li>Source URL visible and clickable</li>
              <li>Site earns the position through ranking</li>
              <li>You can optimize content to win it</li>
              <li>Appears for informational queries</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Knowledge panel</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Structured entity data from Google's Knowledge Graph</li>
              <li>Pulled from Wikipedia, Wikidata, and licensed sources</li>
              <li>You claim it via Google Business Profile or knowledge-panel verification</li>
              <li>Cannot be "optimized for" via content</li>
              <li>Appears for branded and entity queries</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">8 best practices for winning featured snippets</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Target queries you already rank in the top 10 for.</strong> No page-2 result wins a snippet. Start with pages ranking 3-8 for question queries.</li>
          <li><strong>Match the current snippet format.</strong> If the current snippet is a list, structure yours as a list. If it's a paragraph, match paragraph length.</li>
          <li><strong>Use question-based H2s.</strong> "What is [X]?" as an H2 with the answer immediately below beats blog-post prose.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep the answer 40-60 words.</strong> This is the sweet spot Google extracts. Longer answers get truncated with an ellipsis.</li>
          <li><strong>Use clean, semantic HTML.</strong> Real <code>&lt;ol&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;ul&gt;</code>, and <code>&lt;table&gt;</code> — not CSS-styled div soup.</li>
          <li><strong>Include the target keyword in the H2 exactly.</strong> If the query is "how to tie a tie," the H2 should match.</li>
          <li><strong>Answer first, then elaborate.</strong> The first 60 words after the H2 should be the extractable answer. Context and nuance follow.</li>
          <li><strong>Optimize for the "People Also Ask" queries.</strong> Snippets often draw from PAA — winning several PAA questions on one page compounds visibility.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — burying the answer</div>
          <p>Google's extraction algorithm looks for the answer in the first few sentences after the heading. If your page opens with an intro paragraph before the actual answer, you'll lose the snippet to a competitor who leads with the answer.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common featured snippet mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Overwriting the current snippet holder's answer word-for-word</strong> — Google detects near-duplicate content and often keeps the original.</li>
          <li><strong>Formatting a paragraph query as a list</strong> — Google chose paragraph for a reason. Match the format.</li>
          <li><strong>Answer longer than 80 words</strong> — gets truncated, looks worse than a competitor's clean 55-word answer.</li>
          <li><strong>No H2 with the question</strong> — Google needs the semantic pairing of question heading + short answer.</li>
          <li><strong>Writing for the snippet instead of the reader</strong> — Google demotes pages that feel snippet-farmed with no substance below.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring image-carousel and video snippets</strong> — these are growing formats and often the only path to snippet visibility on visual queries.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="how-thestacc-helps">How theStacc helps you win featured snippets</h2>
        <p>Our Content module surfaces snippet opportunities — queries where you rank 3-10 and a snippet exists — then generates the exact structural changes to your page needed to win them. For high-volume informational queries, this is often the single fastest path to a traffic bump. Book a free audit and we'll show you every featured snippet opportunity your site is currently missing.</p>

